There has also been a strong emphasis in recent times, on designing new institutional arrangements and delivery models for supporting the innovation process in many advanced economies (Bachtler and Brown, 2004; Gertler, 2010). Scotland has been very active in this respect and many of its new initiatives have explicitly intended to produce more high potential new starts (Brown and Mason, forthcoming). For example, the largest single project launched by Scottish Enterprise during the last decade or so was the creation of the Intermediate Technology Institutes (ITIs). The rationalewas that in order to aid the development and growth of high technology companies inScotland a radical new model for people and knowledge transfer was required (Brown et al., 2008). This highly ambitious initiative was launched in 2003 as a 10-year programme to promote the creation of new high growth ventures. With an initial allocated funding of £45 m per annum, the ITI programme was designed to promote the development of ‘platform’ technologies in three broad areas of the economy: digital media, energy and life sciences. A separate institution was created for each technology and all three ITIs were made arms-length from Scottish Enterprise so that they could operate in a highly responsive and commercial manner. Each ITI was designed to undertake three core functions, including:


fore-sighting new areas of unexploited research with sizeable market potential;

commissioning research programmes to develop new platform technologies;

commercializing the technology through new venture creation or intellectual property (IP) licensing to existing firms.
